</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Prompt diagnosis of aortoenteric fistulas is imperative for patient survival. The clinical signs of aortoenteric fistula include hematemesis, melena, sepsis, and abdominal pain, but the condition also may be clinically occult. Because clinical signs may not be present or may not be sufficiently specific, imaging is most often necessary to achieve an accurate diagnosis. Although no single imaging modality demonstrates the condition with sufficient sensitivity and specificity, computed tomography (CT), owing to its widespread availability and high efficiency, has become the imaging modality of choice for evaluations in the emergency setting. CT has widely variable sensitivity (40%–90%) and specificity (33%–100%) for the diagnosis of aortoenteric fistulas. To use this modality effectively for the initial diagnostic examination, radiologists must be familiar with the spectrum of CT appearances. Mimics of aortoenteric fistulas include retroperitoneal fibrosis, infected aortic aneurysm, infectious aortitis, and perigraft infection without fistulization. Differentiation is aided by the observation of ectopic gas, loss of the normal fat plane, extravasation of aortic contrast material into the enteric lumen, or leakage of enteric contrast material into the paraprosthetic space; these features are highly suggestive of aortoenteric fistula in a patient with bleeding in the gastrointestinal tract.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291075185">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.291075185">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g01x.jpeg" height="1282" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Primary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old man with severe abdominal pain and hematemesis and no history of abdominal surgery. CT scan shows intraluminal gas (arrow) within the calcified aneurysmal abdominal aorta and loss of the fat plane between the duodenum and the aorta. A large retroperitoneal hematoma is present, and hyperattenuating blood is seen in the bridging fasciae of the left perirenal fat (arrowheads). At surgery, a large abdominal aortic aneurysm was found that had ruptured into the adjacent duodenum and retroperitoneum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g02a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F2A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2a.</b>  Primary aortoduodenal fistula in a 75-year-old man with a cough, massive hematemesis, and melena and with no history of aortic repair. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy showed a large hematoma in the third portion of the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal aortogram shows jetlike extravasation of intravenous contrast material (arrow) from a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer in the aorta into the duodenum (<b>*</b>). Two wall grafts were placed in the infrarenal aorta by interventional radiologists, and prophylactic coil embolization of the gastroduodenal artery was performed. The patient and his family refused any surgical intervention. As the patient’s condition worsened, abdominal and pelvic CT was performed without any intravenous or oral contrast material because of his elevated creatinine level. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows ectopic periaortic gas, soft-tissue thickening (arrow), and loss of the fat pad separating the duodenum (<b>*</b>) from the aorta. Since the patient was given no oral contrast material, the intraluminal contrast material in the proximal small bowel could only have come from the aortographic evaluation performed earlier that day, and its presence helps confirm the diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F2A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g02b.jpeg" height="1142" width="1638" aria-labelledby="F2B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2b.</b>  Primary aortoduodenal fistula in a 75-year-old man with a cough, massive hematemesis, and melena and with no history of aortic repair. Esophagogastroduodenoscopy showed a large hematoma in the third portion of the duodenum. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal aortogram shows jetlike extravasation of intravenous contrast material (arrow) from a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer in the aorta into the duodenum (<b>*</b>). Two wall grafts were placed in the infrarenal aorta by interventional radiologists, and prophylactic coil embolization of the gastroduodenal artery was performed. The patient and his family refused any surgical intervention. As the patient’s condition worsened, abdominal and pelvic CT was performed without any intravenous or oral contrast material because of his elevated creatinine level. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image shows ectopic periaortic gas, soft-tissue thickening (arrow), and loss of the fat pad separating the duodenum (<b>*</b>) from the aorta. Since the patient was given no oral contrast material, the intraluminal contrast material in the proximal small bowel could only have come from the aortographic evaluation performed earlier that day, and its presence helps confirm the diagnosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F2B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g03a.jpeg" height="1674" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 61-year-old man with a 3-week history of intermittent vomiting, recurrent chest pain, and melena and with no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a prevertebral soft-tissue mass with a mottled gas collection (arrow) displacing the partially opacified esophagus (arrowhead) anteriorly. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images show a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, adjacent to the mediastinal soft-tissue mass. At surgery, an aortoesophageal fistula was found. Two Gore excluder cuffs were placed across the defect in the proximal descending aorta. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative esophagogram shows persistent esophageal perforation, with oral contrast material bathing the aortic stent-graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g03b.jpeg" height="1658" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 61-year-old man with a 3-week history of intermittent vomiting, recurrent chest pain, and melena and with no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a prevertebral soft-tissue mass with a mottled gas collection (arrow) displacing the partially opacified esophagus (arrowhead) anteriorly. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images show a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, adjacent to the mediastinal soft-tissue mass. At surgery, an aortoesophageal fistula was found. Two Gore excluder cuffs were placed across the defect in the proximal descending aorta. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative esophagogram shows persistent esophageal perforation, with oral contrast material bathing the aortic stent-graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g03c.jpeg" height="1800" width="815" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 61-year-old man with a 3-week history of intermittent vomiting, recurrent chest pain, and melena and with no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a prevertebral soft-tissue mass with a mottled gas collection (arrow) displacing the partially opacified esophagus (arrowhead) anteriorly. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images show a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, adjacent to the mediastinal soft-tissue mass. At surgery, an aortoesophageal fistula was found. Two Gore excluder cuffs were placed across the defect in the proximal descending aorta. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative esophagogram shows persistent esophageal perforation, with oral contrast material bathing the aortic stent-graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g03d.jpeg" height="1800" width="801" aria-labelledby="F3D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3d.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 61-year-old man with a 3-week history of intermittent vomiting, recurrent chest pain, and melena and with no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced chest CT image shows a prevertebral soft-tissue mass with a mottled gas collection (arrow) displacing the partially opacified esophagus (arrowhead) anteriorly. <b>(b, c)</b> Axial <b>(b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced chest CT images show a penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer (arrow) in the proximal descending aorta, adjacent to the mediastinal soft-tissue mass. At surgery, an aortoesophageal fistula was found. Two Gore excluder cuffs were placed across the defect in the proximal descending aorta. <b>(d)</b> Postoperative esophagogram shows persistent esophageal perforation, with oral contrast material bathing the aortic stent-graft (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F3D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g04a.jpeg" height="1433" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 76-year-old man with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced CT image shows a large hyperattenuating clot (<b>*</b>) in the stomach lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images show an aneurysm in the proximal descending aorta with an associated mediastinal hematoma (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> [soft-tissue window]) and ectopic gas around the main pulmonary artery (arrow in <b>c</b> [lung window]). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced image shows the aneurysm at the isthmus (arrows) and the subjacent hematoma (<b>*</b>). At surgery, aneurysm rupture into the mid-portion of the esophagus was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g04b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1163" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 76-year-old man with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced CT image shows a large hyperattenuating clot (<b>*</b>) in the stomach lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images show an aneurysm in the proximal descending aorta with an associated mediastinal hematoma (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> [soft-tissue window]) and ectopic gas around the main pulmonary artery (arrow in <b>c</b> [lung window]). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced image shows the aneurysm at the isthmus (arrows) and the subjacent hematoma (<b>*</b>). At surgery, aneurysm rupture into the mid-portion of the esophagus was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g04c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1203" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 76-year-old man with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced CT image shows a large hyperattenuating clot (<b>*</b>) in the stomach lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images show an aneurysm in the proximal descending aorta with an associated mediastinal hematoma (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> [soft-tissue window]) and ectopic gas around the main pulmonary artery (arrow in <b>c</b> [lung window]). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced image shows the aneurysm at the isthmus (arrows) and the subjacent hematoma (<b>*</b>). At surgery, aneurysm rupture into the mid-portion of the esophagus was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g04d.jpeg" height="1800" width="1499" aria-labelledby="F4D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4d.</b>  Primary aortoesophageal fistula in a 76-year-old man with back pain. <b>(a)</b> Unenhanced CT image shows a large hyperattenuating clot (<b>*</b>) in the stomach lumen. <b>(b, c)</b> Contrast-enhanced images show an aneurysm in the proximal descending aorta with an associated mediastinal hematoma (<b>*</b> in <b>b</b> [soft-tissue window]) and ectopic gas around the main pulmonary artery (arrow in <b>c</b> [lung window]). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced image shows the aneurysm at the isthmus (arrows) and the subjacent hematoma (<b>*</b>). At surgery, aneurysm rupture into the mid-portion of the esophagus was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F4D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g05a.jpeg" height="1127" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 48-year-old man with persistent bacteremia and a remote history of transabdominal aortobifemoral bypass creation. Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and sagittal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show ectopic perigraft gas (arrow), loss of the fat plane between the third portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and the aortic graft, and partial opacification of the native infrarenal aorta (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). The presence of an aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed at surgery. Multiple enteric pathogens, including <i>E coli</i>, were found in tissue cultures from the aortic graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1373" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 48-year-old man with persistent bacteremia and a remote history of transabdominal aortobifemoral bypass creation. Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and sagittal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show ectopic perigraft gas (arrow), loss of the fat plane between the third portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and the aortic graft, and partial opacification of the native infrarenal aorta (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). The presence of an aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed at surgery. Multiple enteric pathogens, including <i>E coli</i>, were found in tissue cultures from the aortic graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g05c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1296" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 48-year-old man with persistent bacteremia and a remote history of transabdominal aortobifemoral bypass creation. Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and sagittal <b>(c)</b> contrast-enhanced CT images show ectopic perigraft gas (arrow), loss of the fat plane between the third portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) and the aortic graft, and partial opacification of the native infrarenal aorta (arrowhead in <b>a</b>). The presence of an aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed at surgery. Multiple enteric pathogens, including <i>E coli</i>, were found in tissue cultures from the aortic graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g06a.jpeg" height="1190" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old woman with severe back pain, an elevated white blood cell count, and melena 4 years after undergoing an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair with juxtarenal aortobifemoral grafts. The patient also had undergone a left colectomy with creation of a left upper quadrant colostomy for treatment of Crohn disease. <b>(a–d)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> CT images demonstrate a rindlike thickened layer of soft tissue (arrowheads) and ectopic gas (arrow) between the native aortic wrap and the graft, with tethering of a portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) to the abdominal aorta. No CT features of acute Crohn disease are visible. <sup>111</sup>In-tagged white blood cell scanning was performed to rule out aortic graft infection. <b>(e)</b> Coronal image series (with sections arranged in order of anteroposterior progression) obtained with SPECT 20 hours after injection of the tagged white blood cells shows intense radiotracer uptake within the juxtarenal aortobiiliac portion of the graft (straight arrow) and accumulation in the gastrointestinal tract (curved arrow). A region of less intense bone marrow uptake, apparently separate from that in the aorta, is visible in the lumbar spine (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Anterior static 24-hour scintigram shows uptake within the aortic graft (arrow) and further documents the progression of the radiotracer along the distal enteric tract (<b>*</b>) and into the ostomy bag (arrowhead). At surgery, the presence of an infected aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g06b.jpeg" height="1229" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old woman with severe back pain, an elevated white blood cell count, and melena 4 years after undergoing an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair with juxtarenal aortobifemoral grafts. The patient also had undergone a left colectomy with creation of a left upper quadrant colostomy for treatment of Crohn disease. <b>(a–d)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> CT images demonstrate a rindlike thickened layer of soft tissue (arrowheads) and ectopic gas (arrow) between the native aortic wrap and the graft, with tethering of a portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) to the abdominal aorta. No CT features of acute Crohn disease are visible. <sup>111</sup>In-tagged white blood cell scanning was performed to rule out aortic graft infection. <b>(e)</b> Coronal image series (with sections arranged in order of anteroposterior progression) obtained with SPECT 20 hours after injection of the tagged white blood cells shows intense radiotracer uptake within the juxtarenal aortobiiliac portion of the graft (straight arrow) and accumulation in the gastrointestinal tract (curved arrow). A region of less intense bone marrow uptake, apparently separate from that in the aorta, is visible in the lumbar spine (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Anterior static 24-hour scintigram shows uptake within the aortic graft (arrow) and further documents the progression of the radiotracer along the distal enteric tract (<b>*</b>) and into the ostomy bag (arrowhead). At surgery, the presence of an infected aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g06c.jpeg" height="1800" width="924" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old woman with severe back pain, an elevated white blood cell count, and melena 4 years after undergoing an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair with juxtarenal aortobifemoral grafts. The patient also had undergone a left colectomy with creation of a left upper quadrant colostomy for treatment of Crohn disease. <b>(a–d)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> CT images demonstrate a rindlike thickened layer of soft tissue (arrowheads) and ectopic gas (arrow) between the native aortic wrap and the graft, with tethering of a portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) to the abdominal aorta. No CT features of acute Crohn disease are visible. <sup>111</sup>In-tagged white blood cell scanning was performed to rule out aortic graft infection. <b>(e)</b> Coronal image series (with sections arranged in order of anteroposterior progression) obtained with SPECT 20 hours after injection of the tagged white blood cells shows intense radiotracer uptake within the juxtarenal aortobiiliac portion of the graft (straight arrow) and accumulation in the gastrointestinal tract (curved arrow). A region of less intense bone marrow uptake, apparently separate from that in the aorta, is visible in the lumbar spine (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Anterior static 24-hour scintigram shows uptake within the aortic graft (arrow) and further documents the progression of the radiotracer along the distal enteric tract (<b>*</b>) and into the ostomy bag (arrowhead). At surgery, the presence of an infected aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g06d.jpeg" height="1800" width="939" aria-labelledby="F6D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6d.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old woman with severe back pain, an elevated white blood cell count, and melena 4 years after undergoing an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair with juxtarenal aortobifemoral grafts. The patient also had undergone a left colectomy with creation of a left upper quadrant colostomy for treatment of Crohn disease. <b>(a–d)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> CT images demonstrate a rindlike thickened layer of soft tissue (arrowheads) and ectopic gas (arrow) between the native aortic wrap and the graft, with tethering of a portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) to the abdominal aorta. No CT features of acute Crohn disease are visible. <sup>111</sup>In-tagged white blood cell scanning was performed to rule out aortic graft infection. <b>(e)</b> Coronal image series (with sections arranged in order of anteroposterior progression) obtained with SPECT 20 hours after injection of the tagged white blood cells shows intense radiotracer uptake within the juxtarenal aortobiiliac portion of the graft (straight arrow) and accumulation in the gastrointestinal tract (curved arrow). A region of less intense bone marrow uptake, apparently separate from that in the aorta, is visible in the lumbar spine (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Anterior static 24-hour scintigram shows uptake within the aortic graft (arrow) and further documents the progression of the radiotracer along the distal enteric tract (<b>*</b>) and into the ostomy bag (arrowhead). At surgery, the presence of an infected aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F6D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g06e.jpeg" height="1209" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6e.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old woman with severe back pain, an elevated white blood cell count, and melena 4 years after undergoing an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair with juxtarenal aortobifemoral grafts. The patient also had undergone a left colectomy with creation of a left upper quadrant colostomy for treatment of Crohn disease. <b>(a–d)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> CT images demonstrate a rindlike thickened layer of soft tissue (arrowheads) and ectopic gas (arrow) between the native aortic wrap and the graft, with tethering of a portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) to the abdominal aorta. No CT features of acute Crohn disease are visible. <sup>111</sup>In-tagged white blood cell scanning was performed to rule out aortic graft infection. <b>(e)</b> Coronal image series (with sections arranged in order of anteroposterior progression) obtained with SPECT 20 hours after injection of the tagged white blood cells shows intense radiotracer uptake within the juxtarenal aortobiiliac portion of the graft (straight arrow) and accumulation in the gastrointestinal tract (curved arrow). A region of less intense bone marrow uptake, apparently separate from that in the aorta, is visible in the lumbar spine (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Anterior static 24-hour scintigram shows uptake within the aortic graft (arrow) and further documents the progression of the radiotracer along the distal enteric tract (<b>*</b>) and into the ostomy bag (arrowhead). At surgery, the presence of an infected aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F6E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6F" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g06f.jpeg" height="1800" width="1037" aria-labelledby="F6F" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6f.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 73-year-old woman with severe back pain, an elevated white blood cell count, and melena 4 years after undergoing an abdominal aortic aneurysm repair with juxtarenal aortobifemoral grafts. The patient also had undergone a left colectomy with creation of a left upper quadrant colostomy for treatment of Crohn disease. <b>(a–d)</b> Unenhanced axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and contrast-enhanced axial <b>(b)</b>, coronal <b>(c)</b>, and sagittal <b>(d)</b> CT images demonstrate a rindlike thickened layer of soft tissue (arrowheads) and ectopic gas (arrow) between the native aortic wrap and the graft, with tethering of a portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) to the abdominal aorta. No CT features of acute Crohn disease are visible. <sup>111</sup>In-tagged white blood cell scanning was performed to rule out aortic graft infection. <b>(e)</b> Coronal image series (with sections arranged in order of anteroposterior progression) obtained with SPECT 20 hours after injection of the tagged white blood cells shows intense radiotracer uptake within the juxtarenal aortobiiliac portion of the graft (straight arrow) and accumulation in the gastrointestinal tract (curved arrow). A region of less intense bone marrow uptake, apparently separate from that in the aorta, is visible in the lumbar spine (arrowhead). <b>(f)</b> Anterior static 24-hour scintigram shows uptake within the aortic graft (arrow) and further documents the progression of the radiotracer along the distal enteric tract (<b>*</b>) and into the ostomy bag (arrowhead). At surgery, the presence of an infected aortic graft–duodenal fistula was confirmed.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F6F">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g07a.jpeg" height="1288" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 70-year-old man with severe back pain and massive hematochezia after undergoing surgical repair of an abdominal aortic aneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows bulging of the right anterior aortic wall into the third portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) and loss of the fat plane between the two. <sup>99m</sup>Tc-tagged red blood cell scanning was performed to determine the source of gastrointestinal bleeding. <b>(b, c)</b> Frontal <b>(b)</b> and lateral <b>(c)</b> static scintigrams, obtained at 90 minutes after the tagged red blood cell injection, show the large amount of radiotracer that initially accumulated within the expected region of the retroperitoneal duodenum (<b>*</b>) and then spread both proximally and distally. At surgery, the presence of an aortoduodenal fistula was confirmed. <i>Ant.</i> = anterior, <i>Post.</i> = posterior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g07b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1435" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 70-year-old man with severe back pain and massive hematochezia after undergoing surgical repair of an abdominal aortic aneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows bulging of the right anterior aortic wall into the third portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) and loss of the fat plane between the two. <sup>99m</sup>Tc-tagged red blood cell scanning was performed to determine the source of gastrointestinal bleeding. <b>(b, c)</b> Frontal <b>(b)</b> and lateral <b>(c)</b> static scintigrams, obtained at 90 minutes after the tagged red blood cell injection, show the large amount of radiotracer that initially accumulated within the expected region of the retroperitoneal duodenum (<b>*</b>) and then spread both proximally and distally. At surgery, the presence of an aortoduodenal fistula was confirmed. <i>Ant.</i> = anterior, <i>Post.</i> = posterior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g07c.jpeg" height="1710" width="1369" aria-labelledby="F7C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7c.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 70-year-old man with severe back pain and massive hematochezia after undergoing surgical repair of an abdominal aortic aneurysm. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows bulging of the right anterior aortic wall into the third portion of the duodenum (<b>*</b>) and loss of the fat plane between the two. <sup>99m</sup>Tc-tagged red blood cell scanning was performed to determine the source of gastrointestinal bleeding. <b>(b, c)</b> Frontal <b>(b)</b> and lateral <b>(c)</b> static scintigrams, obtained at 90 minutes after the tagged red blood cell injection, show the large amount of radiotracer that initially accumulated within the expected region of the retroperitoneal duodenum (<b>*</b>) and then spread both proximally and distally. At surgery, the presence of an aortoduodenal fistula was confirmed. <i>Ant.</i> = anterior, <i>Post.</i> = posterior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F7C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g08a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1732" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Secondary aortoesophageal fistula in a 63-year-old man with hematemesis and fever who had a history of thoracic aortic aneurysm repair. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced chest CT images (<b>a</b> [soft-tissue window] at the same level as <b>b</b> [lung window]) show a thick rindlike layer of soft tissue around the graft (arrowhead), gas collections (arrow), and an ill-defined fat plane separating the aorta from the esophagus. <b>(c)</b> Swallow study shows oral water-soluble contrast material that has leaked from the distal esophagus and bathes the aortic graft (arrow). The diagnosis of a secondary aortoesophageal fistula was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g08b.jpeg" height="1455" width="1530" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Secondary aortoesophageal fistula in a 63-year-old man with hematemesis and fever who had a history of thoracic aortic aneurysm repair. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced chest CT images (<b>a</b> [soft-tissue window] at the same level as <b>b</b> [lung window]) show a thick rindlike layer of soft tissue around the graft (arrowhead), gas collections (arrow), and an ill-defined fat plane separating the aorta from the esophagus. <b>(c)</b> Swallow study shows oral water-soluble contrast material that has leaked from the distal esophagus and bathes the aortic graft (arrow). The diagnosis of a secondary aortoesophageal fistula was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g08c.jpeg" height="1800" width="888" aria-labelledby="F8C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8c.</b>  Secondary aortoesophageal fistula in a 63-year-old man with hematemesis and fever who had a history of thoracic aortic aneurysm repair. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced chest CT images (<b>a</b> [soft-tissue window] at the same level as <b>b</b> [lung window]) show a thick rindlike layer of soft tissue around the graft (arrowhead), gas collections (arrow), and an ill-defined fat plane separating the aorta from the esophagus. <b>(c)</b> Swallow study shows oral water-soluble contrast material that has leaked from the distal esophagus and bathes the aortic graft (arrow). The diagnosis of a secondary aortoesophageal fistula was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F8C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g09a.jpeg" height="1725" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula and pseudoaneurysm formation in an 87-year-old woman with acute hematemesis and a remote history of a Billroth II procedure and aortobiiliac graft placement. Unenhanced CT was performed because of the patient’s elevated creatinine level. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and oblique axial <b>(b)</b> CT images demonstrate a heterogeneously attenuating mass (<b>*</b>) anterior to the right external iliac artery graft (arrows), with notable loss of the fat plane between the mass and bowel (arrowheads). To verify these findings, abdominal US was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Power <b>(c)</b> and color <b>(d)</b> Doppler US images show the classic “yin-yang” sign of a pseudoaneurysm in the right lower quadrant. The intimate relationship between the pseudoaneurysm and a small bowel loop is highly suggestive of an arterioenteric fistula, and this diagnosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g09b.jpeg" height="1393" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula and pseudoaneurysm formation in an 87-year-old woman with acute hematemesis and a remote history of a Billroth II procedure and aortobiiliac graft placement. Unenhanced CT was performed because of the patient’s elevated creatinine level. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and oblique axial <b>(b)</b> CT images demonstrate a heterogeneously attenuating mass (<b>*</b>) anterior to the right external iliac artery graft (arrows), with notable loss of the fat plane between the mass and bowel (arrowheads). To verify these findings, abdominal US was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Power <b>(c)</b> and color <b>(d)</b> Doppler US images show the classic “yin-yang” sign of a pseudoaneurysm in the right lower quadrant. The intimate relationship between the pseudoaneurysm and a small bowel loop is highly suggestive of an arterioenteric fistula, and this diagnosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22c09c.jpeg" height="970" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula and pseudoaneurysm formation in an 87-year-old woman with acute hematemesis and a remote history of a Billroth II procedure and aortobiiliac graft placement. Unenhanced CT was performed because of the patient’s elevated creatinine level. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and oblique axial <b>(b)</b> CT images demonstrate a heterogeneously attenuating mass (<b>*</b>) anterior to the right external iliac artery graft (arrows), with notable loss of the fat plane between the mass and bowel (arrowheads). To verify these findings, abdominal US was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Power <b>(c)</b> and color <b>(d)</b> Doppler US images show the classic “yin-yang” sign of a pseudoaneurysm in the right lower quadrant. The intimate relationship between the pseudoaneurysm and a small bowel loop is highly suggestive of an arterioenteric fistula, and this diagnosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22c09d.jpeg" height="970" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F9D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9d.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula and pseudoaneurysm formation in an 87-year-old woman with acute hematemesis and a remote history of a Billroth II procedure and aortobiiliac graft placement. Unenhanced CT was performed because of the patient’s elevated creatinine level. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial <b>(a)</b> and oblique axial <b>(b)</b> CT images demonstrate a heterogeneously attenuating mass (<b>*</b>) anterior to the right external iliac artery graft (arrows), with notable loss of the fat plane between the mass and bowel (arrowheads). To verify these findings, abdominal US was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Power <b>(c)</b> and color <b>(d)</b> Doppler US images show the classic “yin-yang” sign of a pseudoaneurysm in the right lower quadrant. The intimate relationship between the pseudoaneurysm and a small bowel loop is highly suggestive of an arterioenteric fistula, and this diagnosis was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F9D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g10a.jpeg" height="1239" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 53-year-old woman with hematemesis 6 months after an aortobifemoral bypass graft revision for infection. Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and three-dimensional volume-rendered <b>(c)</b> CT images show perigraft fluid, loss of the fat plane separating the duodenum (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) from the aortic graft, and formation of a graft pseudoaneurysm (arrow) immediately proximal to the origins of the common iliac arteries (arrowheads in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>). Note the advantage of multiplanar reformatting over three-dimensional volume rendering for depicting soft-tissue thickening, which is visible around the pseudoaneurysm in <b>b</b> but not in <b>c</b>. At surgery, an infrarenal aortic graft pseudoaneurysm, an aortoduodenal fistula, and complete breakdown of the aortic graft were found. The patient died during surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g10b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1426" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 53-year-old woman with hematemesis 6 months after an aortobifemoral bypass graft revision for infection. Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and three-dimensional volume-rendered <b>(c)</b> CT images show perigraft fluid, loss of the fat plane separating the duodenum (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) from the aortic graft, and formation of a graft pseudoaneurysm (arrow) immediately proximal to the origins of the common iliac arteries (arrowheads in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>). Note the advantage of multiplanar reformatting over three-dimensional volume rendering for depicting soft-tissue thickening, which is visible around the pseudoaneurysm in <b>b</b> but not in <b>c</b>. At surgery, an infrarenal aortic graft pseudoaneurysm, an aortoduodenal fistula, and complete breakdown of the aortic graft were found. The patient died during surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22c10c.jpeg" height="1280" width="425" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Secondary aortoduodenal fistula in a 53-year-old woman with hematemesis 6 months after an aortobifemoral bypass graft revision for infection. Axial <b>(a)</b>, coronal <b>(b)</b>, and three-dimensional volume-rendered <b>(c)</b> CT images show perigraft fluid, loss of the fat plane separating the duodenum (<b>*</b> in <b>a</b>) from the aortic graft, and formation of a graft pseudoaneurysm (arrow) immediately proximal to the origins of the common iliac arteries (arrowheads in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>). Note the advantage of multiplanar reformatting over three-dimensional volume rendering for depicting soft-tissue thickening, which is visible around the pseudoaneurysm in <b>b</b> but not in <b>c</b>. At surgery, an infrarenal aortic graft pseudoaneurysm, an aortoduodenal fistula, and complete breakdown of the aortic graft were found. The patient died during surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g11a.jpeg" height="1247" width="1674" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Retroperitoneal fibrosis in a middle-aged man with worsening back pain and no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) show a rindlike region of soft-tissue fibrosis (arrows) encasing the aorta, bilateral common iliac arteries, and both ureters. Mild dilatation of the bilateral proximal urinary collecting systems also is visible and is more pronounced on the right than on the left; there is less enhancement of the right renal parenchyma than of the left. <b>(c)</b> Renal scintigram obtained with <sup>99m</sup>Tc mertiatide shows delayed excretion of radiotracer by the right kidney. Unlike aortoenteric fistula, retroperitoneal fibrosis is not associated with periaortic ectopic gas. <i>POST</i> = posterior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g11b.jpeg" height="1358" width="1692" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Retroperitoneal fibrosis in a middle-aged man with worsening back pain and no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) show a rindlike region of soft-tissue fibrosis (arrows) encasing the aorta, bilateral common iliac arteries, and both ureters. Mild dilatation of the bilateral proximal urinary collecting systems also is visible and is more pronounced on the right than on the left; there is less enhancement of the right renal parenchyma than of the left. <b>(c)</b> Renal scintigram obtained with <sup>99m</sup>Tc mertiatide shows delayed excretion of radiotracer by the right kidney. Unlike aortoenteric fistula, retroperitoneal fibrosis is not associated with periaortic ectopic gas. <i>POST</i> = posterior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g11c.jpeg" height="1800" width="1362" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Retroperitoneal fibrosis in a middle-aged man with worsening back pain and no history of aortic surgery. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) show a rindlike region of soft-tissue fibrosis (arrows) encasing the aorta, bilateral common iliac arteries, and both ureters. Mild dilatation of the bilateral proximal urinary collecting systems also is visible and is more pronounced on the right than on the left; there is less enhancement of the right renal parenchyma than of the left. <b>(c)</b> Renal scintigram obtained with <sup>99m</sup>Tc mertiatide shows delayed excretion of radiotracer by the right kidney. Unlike aortoenteric fistula, retroperitoneal fibrosis is not associated with periaortic ectopic gas. <i>POST</i> = posterior.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g12a.jpeg" height="1282" width="1728" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Infected (mycotic) aortic aneurysm in a 52-year-old white man with a sudden onset of severe abdominal pain radiating to his back after a 2-week history of flulike symptoms. A blood culture was positive for group A <i>Streptococcus</i>. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows periaortic fat stranding that obscures the margins of the mildly dilated abdominal aorta. <b>(b)</b> Abdominal aortogram shows a saccular aneurysm of the infrarenal aorta (arrow), immediately above the bifurcation. The presence of an infected infrarenal aortic aneurysm was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g12b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1433" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Infected (mycotic) aortic aneurysm in a 52-year-old white man with a sudden onset of severe abdominal pain radiating to his back after a 2-week history of flulike symptoms. A blood culture was positive for group A <i>Streptococcus</i>. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT scan shows periaortic fat stranding that obscures the margins of the mildly dilated abdominal aorta. <b>(b)</b> Abdominal aortogram shows a saccular aneurysm of the infrarenal aorta (arrow), immediately above the bifurcation. The presence of an infected infrarenal aortic aneurysm was confirmed at surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g13a.jpeg" height="1384" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Aortitis in a 91-year-old woman with worsening abdominal pain and an elevated white blood cell count. Contrast-enhanced CT scans (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) obtained at her admission show intramural gas in the abdominal aorta (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and a large apple core–like colonic mass at the hepatic flexure (arrows in <b>b</b>). <i>C septicum</i> grew in blood cultures. Because of the patient’s advanced age, a long course of antibiotic therapy was completed before surgical exploration was performed. At surgery, a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the hepatic flexure was found, with no signs of residual aortic infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22g13b.jpeg" height="1384" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Aortitis in a 91-year-old woman with worsening abdominal pain and an elevated white blood cell count. Contrast-enhanced CT scans (<b>a</b> at a higher level than <b>b</b>) obtained at her admission show intramural gas in the abdominal aorta (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) and a large apple core–like colonic mass at the hepatic flexure (arrows in <b>b</b>). <i>C septicum</i> grew in blood cultures. Because of the patient’s advanced age, a long course of antibiotic therapy was completed before surgical exploration was performed. At surgery, a moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma of the hepatic flexure was found, with no signs of residual aortic infection.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.291075185&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>CT Features Associated with Aortoenteric Fistula and Perigraft Infection</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.291075185/asset/images/g09ja22t01x.jpeg" height="654" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /><div class="notes"><div role="doc-footnote">Note.—Most CT signs of aortoenteric fistula are nonspecific and may be seen in perigraft infection without fistulization, retroperitoneal fibrosis, or infectious aortitis, or in absence of any of these conditions. Clinical findings must be considered in the differential diagnosis. X = common, XX = more common.</div></div></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Voorhoeve</span