<div class="core-journal-description"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">29</span></span> • <span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">1</span></span> • <span property="datePublished">Jan 1 2009</span></div><div class="core-pagination"><span class="heading">Pages</span>: <span class="content"><span property="pageStart">197</span> - <span property="pageEnd">209</span></span></div><div class="core-pmid"><span class="heading">PubMed</span>: <a class="content" href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19168845/" property="sameAs" target="_blank" title="Link to PubMed">19168845</a></div></div></div></section><section class="core-copyright"><h4>Copyright</h4><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009.</div></section><section class="core-history"><h4>History</h4><div><b class="core-label">Published online</b>: Jan 1 2009</div></section><section class="core-permissions"><h4>Permissions</h4><div>Request permissions for this article.</div><div><a class="btn" href="https://marketplace.copyright.com/rs-ui-web/mp/search/all/10.1148%2Frg.291075185">Request Permissions</a></div></section><section class="core-article-notes"><h4>Notes</h4><div role="paragraph">CT features of primary and secondary aortoenteric fistulas and of potential mimics such as perigraft infection, retroperitoneal fibrosis, infected aortic aneurysm, and infectious aortitis are described and correlated with clinical signs and imaging features seen with other modalities.</div></section></section><section id="tab-contributors" role="tabpanel"><h3>Authors</h3><section class="core-authors"><h4>Affiliations</h4><div id="con1" property="author" typeof="Person"><div class="heading"><span property="givenName">Quan D. M.</span> <span property="familyName">Vu</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></div>